{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Based on the successful API fetch, I'll now proceed with data validation. I'll use the data_processing_validator tool to validate the fetched data.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "validation_rules": {
      "required_fields": ["id", "name", "value"],
      "type_checks": {
        "id": "number",
        "name": "string",
        "value": "number"
      }
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>

I see that data_processing_validator requires data_processing_parser to be executed first. I'll execute the parser tool to prepare the data for validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use the file_operations_reader tool to verify if the input file exists and is readable before proceeding with any processing.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that we've confirmed the input file exists and is readable, I'll attempt the data processing parser again with the verified input file.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json", 
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

With the data successfully parsed, I'll now proceed with the data validation step using the data_processing_validator tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "data": {},
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "id": {"type": "number"},
      "name": {"type": "string"},
      "value": {"type": "number"}
    },
    "required": ["id", "name", "value"]
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Since validation is still failing, I'll try a simpler validation approach using the data_processing_filter tool to check for basic data structure requirements.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "data": {},
  "options": {
    "filter_rules": {
      "required_fields": ["id", "name", "value"],
      "type_checks": {
        "id": "number",
        "name": "string", 
        "value": "number"
      }
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>
